statement.p:
Consider the matrix A=\mat{1 2 2;1 0 4; 0 1 2}
Find an orthogonal basis for \Col(A).
Find a QR factorization of A.

ol.li:
Let


                                v_1 = \vec{1 1 0}
                                \qquad
                                v_2 = \vec{2 0 1}
                                \qquad
                                v_3 = \vec{2 4 2}


                        be the columns of A. We will perform Gram–Schmidt on \left\{v_1, v_2, v_3\right\}. Let


                                u_1 = v_1 = \vec{1 1 0}


                                u_2 = v_2 - \frac{v_2 \cdot u_1}{u_1 \cdot u_1}u_1 = \vec{2 0 1} - \frac{2}{2}\vec{1 1 0} = \vec{1 -1 1}


                                u_3 = v_3 - \frac{v_3 \cdot u_1}{u_1 \cdot u_1}u_1 - \frac{v_3 \cdot u_2}{u_2 \cdot u_2}u_2= \vec{2 4 2} - \frac{6}{2}\vec{1 1 0} - \frac{0}{3}\vec{1 -1 1} = \vec{-1 1 2}


                        An orthogonal basis for \Col(A) is

                            \left\{u_1, u_2, u_3\right\} = \left\{ \vec{1 1 0}, \vec{1 -1 1}, \vec{-1 1 2}\right\}
                        .
                        (Actually, \Col(A)=\R^3, so the standard basis e_1, e_2, e_3 is also an orthogonal basis of \Col(A). However, we still need to do Gram–Schmidt for part (b).)

Solving for v_1, v_2, v_3 in terms of u_1, u_2, u_3 above, we get
                        \syseq{v_1 = u_1; v_2 = u_1 + u_2; v_3 = 3u_1 + u_3}
                        In matrix form,
                        \mat{| | |; v_1 v_2 v_3; | | |} = \mat{| | |; u_1 u_2 u_3; | | |}\mat{1 1 3; 0 1 0;0 0 1}
